<!-- CONTENT -->
<div class="cs-content">

  <div class="reveal">
    <p class="label">Overview</p>
    <h2>The Problem</h2>
    <p>A rapidly scaling B2B SaaS company had built a powerful CRM — but their sales teams were abandoning it. Onboarding took up to 14 days. Support tickets were rising 40% quarter-over-quarter. The AI features meant to be their differentiator were largely invisible to users.</p>
    <p>My mandate: redesign the system from a behavioral standpoint — not just visually, but architecturally — to reduce cognitive load and surface AI capabilities in ways that felt intuitive, not intrusive.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="cs-outcomes-grid reveal">
    <div class="cs-outcome">
      <div class="cs-outcome-val">62%</div>
      <div class="cs-outcome-label">Faster Onboarding</div>
    </div>
    <div class="cs-outcome">
      <div class="cs-outcome-val">3.4×</div>
      <div class="cs-outcome-label">Daily Active Usage</div>
    </div>
    <div class="cs-outcome">
      <div class="cs-outcome-val">91</div>
      <div class="cs-outcome-label">NPS Score (was 34)</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="reveal">
    <p class="label">Research</p>
    <h2>Understanding the Real Problem</h2>
    <p>I conducted 18 contextual user interviews across 3 user segments: sales reps, team leads, and ops managers. Each had distinct mental models and pain points. The unifying thread: the system's information architecture matched how the engineers thought — not how salespeople worked.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="cs-callout reveal">
    <p>"I'm not a bad salesperson. I'm just bad at navigating this system while I'm on a call."</p>
  </div>

  <div class="cs-img-placeholder reveal">[ Research synthesis board — affinity mapping + journey map ]</div>

  <div class="reveal">
    <p class="label">Process</p>
    <h2>Design Approach</h2>
    <p>I applied a behavioral design lens: mapping every friction point to a cognitive principle — recall vs. recognition, decision fatigue, working memory overload. Then I redesigned the information hierarchy around sales reps' actual workflows, not the product team's mental model of those workflows.</p>
    <p>AI features were repositioned from a "features tab" into contextual nudges embedded exactly where and when they were relevant — reducing the learning curve from "how do I use AI?" to "it's just part of how this works."</p>
  </div>

  <div class="cs-two-col reveal">
    <div class="cs-img-placeholder" style="min-height:240px;">[ Before: Complex navigation — 8 levels deep ]</div>
    <div class="cs-img-placeholder" style="min-height:240px;">[ After: Context-first layout — 3 steps max ]</div>
  </div>

  <div class="cs-img-placeholder reveal">[ High-fidelity wireframes — key flows: lead entry, AI suggestion panel, pipeline view ]</div>

  <div class="reveal">
    <p class="label">Testing</p>
    <h2>Validation & Iteration</h2>
    <p>Three rounds of usability testing with Maze, followed by a 6-week beta with 120 users across 4 enterprise accounts. We measured task completion, time-on-task, error rate, and NPS after each iteration. Each round cut an average of 2.3 steps from the critical paths.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="cs-img-placeholder reveal">[ Usability test session recordings — annotated key moments ]</div>

  <div class="reveal">
    <p class="label">Outcome</p>
    <h2>Results</h2>
    <p>At launch, the redesign achieved a 62% reduction in onboarding time (14 days → 5.3 days average). Daily active usage increased 3.4× over 90 days. NPS jumped from 34 to 91. The AI feature adoption rate went from 8% to 61%. The company used the redesign in their Series B fundraising deck.</p>
  </div>

